commentBody:
@Steve L  & @Teresa - yes, the local Brit in Kentucky which explains my lack of appreciation for college basketball (and NASCAR) which bemuses my neighbo(u)rs while they struggle to understand me.  As I point out, I'm not the one with the accent.

As Steve noted in another comment, one thing about xwords is that we learn stuff, and I especially enjoy coming to these comments.  I did not know that Cluedo was a composite of Clue and Ludo; nor did I know that Parcheesi was simply the US name (and, IMO, a better name) for Ludo.  OTOH a word like ARGOT was almost a gimme for me but I hadn't realized until ('TIL? 'FORE?) today that the word is almost unknown to many Americans.  

And later this week it will be exactly 40 years since I came to the US - at the time I thought it would be for a few months.  As John Lennon said, life is what happens while you are making other plans.

@Bruce 
On Monday or Tuesday, O'Hara plantation would have been a clue for TARA. On Wednesday though Sunday, that's too easy of a clue.  :)

...........................................

@Margaret I was shocked by that too, unless it's some sort of drug reference I happily don't know anything about. I don't like seeing those in the puzzle anyway.

Which brings me to the cluing. Good puzzle, clever theme, but when there's an already vague clue like Prosecution figs. and it actually refers to persons, it definitely calls for a question mark to indicate wordplay. A number of the clues were like this, so far off as to take the fun out of it, in entries too short to be worth the effort. 

And despite the constructor's praiseworthy attempts, there was some crosswordese so stale you could taste the OLEO going rancid, to say nothing of far too many sports and entertainment entries for my liking. No offense to the constructor, who did a good job with a clever idea, but there have been so many really good puzzles with great, clever cluing in recent weeks that this one fell flat for me. Just my opinion!

@Chrissy 
I tried LINGO first, as PATOIS would not fit.  Likewise JARGON and PIDGIN were nonstarters.
Lots of choices before ARGOT emerged, assisted by the SHARK and the ORGY

@James 

I think you'd be better off giving examples of which clues you thought were poor, and why.  Speculating about the constructor's motives when you really have no idea what they were is pointless, and seems like the faux cleverness you appear to find in the cluing.

Plus, this is a forum for solvers.  The editors may or may not look at it.

@James 
Dear Editor,

Stop trying to make me care about women's basketball. I understand that Caitlin Clark is the bright, shiny object of the moment, but come on. A coach? I would have been fine with TARA Lipinsky.

@Grant
We rewatched it recently and it does hold up. 
Also, the movie has been made into a stage play. We took our granddaughter and we all thoroughly enjoyed it.

@Asher 

For what it's worth, this is hardly the first time that letters have been in secret places, like the black squares or outside the grid.

As to why the dark squares are like secret passages, they allow the full answer to continue into the next set of white squares (twice).

@Peter 

I finished today's puzzle, which was very clever, a number of hours ago and saw the Wordle spoiler post.  

However, after going back to sleep I had the great fortune of forgetting the word entirely.  The (few) benefits of advanced age and insomnia.

@Jim 
I do the Wordle in the night, along with the Bee, the new Strands, the Connection, and the LetterBox.  Then I play a few games (WWF, Word Chums, Scrabble).  Then I read a chapter in my current book.  ...and then I go back to sleep.  The Crossword puzzle goes with pre-breakfast coffee, and Comments are read post-solve.
This keeps me safe from harm.  I got the Wordle in 3 ....but now I can't recall what it was....LOL

@Ken S 
I agree with all of your objections...but these (as we are often told) are clues, not defintions.  It pleases some editors to release their inner fiends, especially on the late-week puzzles. Do you think maybe some of them are "shooting up" (right into a VEIN) when they work on the clues?

I still remember my dad's serial number; there aren't any letters in front of it....but he was from an earlier time (before WWII.)  I still have my dogtags...no number at all.

@Mean Old Lady 
Antes are small amounts that everyone on a poker table pays to play a hand.
Blinds are unit bets by two players at a poker table (usually some version of Hold-em) that rotate around the table. Tournaments typically use blinds to steadily increase the stakes over time.

@Eliz 
Oddly, I never even thought of healthcare for that clue. Illicit drugs were all that ever entered my mind. A shot of heroin is often mainlined into a vein. 

Not saying that's what the constructor had in mind, but just pointing out a different way of looking at clue 19D.

@cipherdom 

One you've solved it you should get the reveal. Several of the black squares are actually SECRET PASSAGES which contain letters which make sense of the few answers that don't add up. So MANE is revealed as part of MANEATINGSHARK, and PRIMER is part of PRIMEREALESTATE.

I thought it was super-clever and even more fun because I didn't get it til it was revealed..

@Steve 

You must have myth'd something along the way. 



Do emus like fermented fruit?

@Laura D 

Blinds, the last two hands of the first round of betting pre-bets set amounts (these are called the small and big blind - the big blind is roughly double the small and bets last)


Antes, everyone contributes a preset amount before you see your cards
